# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The second question of the 1967 Australian referendum of 27 May 1967, called by the Holt government, related to Indigenous Australians.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Voters were asked whether to give the Commonwealth Parliament the power to make special laws for Indigenous Australians, and whether Indigenous Australians should be included in official population counts for constitutional purposes.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The term "the Aboriginal Race" was used in the question.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Technically the referendum question was a vote on the Constitution Alteration (Aboriginals) 1967 that would amend section 51(xxvi) and repeal section 127.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendments to the Constitution were overwhelmingly endorsed, winning 90.77% of votes cast and having majority support in all six states.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendment became law on 10 August 1967.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1901, the attorney-general, Alfred Deakin, provided a legal opinion on the meaning of section 127 of the Constitution of Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 127 excluded "aboriginal natives" from being counted when reckoning the numbers of the people of the commonwealth or a state.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] His legal advice was that "half-castes" were not "aboriginal natives".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Prior to 1967, censuses asked a question about Aboriginal race to establish numbers of "half-castes" and "full-bloods".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] "Full-bloods" were then subtracted from the official population figure in accordance with the legal advice from the attorney-general.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Strong activism by individuals and both Indigenous and non-Indigenous groups greatly aided the success of the 1967 referendum in the years leading up to the vote.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Calls for Aboriginal issues to be dealt with at the federal level began as early as 1910.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From here, the overall plight of Aboriginal Australians became a fundamental political issue.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On 7 April 1965, the Menzies Cabinet decided that it would seek to repeal section 127 of the Constitution at the same time as it sought to amend the nexus provision, but made no firm plans or timetable for such action.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In August 1965, attorney-general Billy Snedden proposed to Cabinet that abolition of section 127 was inappropriate unless section 51(xxvi) was simultaneously amended to remove the words "other than the aboriginal race in any state".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] He was rebuffed, but gained agreement when he made a similar submission to the Holt Cabinet in 1966.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the meantime, his Liberal colleague Billy Wentworth had introduced a private member's bill proposing *inter alia* to amend section 51(xxvi).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1964, the Leader of the Opposition, Arthur Calwell, had proposed such a change and pledged that his party, the Australian Labor Party, would back any referendum to that effect.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1967, the Australian Parliament was unanimous in voting for the alteration bill.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Voters were asked to approve, together, changes to two provisions in the Constitution section 51(xxvi) and section 127.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] And the extraordinary clauses that follow (ordinarily referred to as heads of power) list most of the legislative powers of the federal parliament.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendment gave the Commonwealth parliament power to make "special laws" with respect to Aboriginal People living in a state; the parliament already had unfettered power in regard to territories under section 122 of the Constitution.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Constitution required the calculation of "the people" for several purposes in sections 24, 89, 93 and 105.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 89 related to the imposition of uniform customs duties and operated until 1901.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 93 related to uniform custom duties after being imposed by section 89 and operated until 1908.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 105 related to taking over state debts and was superseded by section 105A inserted in the Constitution in 1929 following the 1928 referendum.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Accordingly, in 1967, only section 24 in relation to the House of Representatives had any operational importance to section 127.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 24 "requires the membership of the House of Representatives to be distributed among the States in proportion to the respective numbers of their people".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The number of people in section 24 is calculated using the latest statistics of the Commonwealth which are derived from the census.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 51(xi) of the Constitution enabled the Parliament to make laws for "census and statistics" and it exercised that power to pass the *Census and Statistics Act 1905*.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] At this time, territorians, while able and required to vote in elections, were not permitted to vote in referendums.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is frequently stated that the 1967 referendum gave Aboriginal people Australian citizenship and that it gave them the right to vote in federal elections; however, this was not the case.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From 1944, Aboriginal people in Western Australia could apply to become citizens of the state, which gave them various rights, including the right to vote.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This citizenship was conditional on adopting "the manner and habits of civilised life" and not associating with Aboriginal people other than their parents, siblings, children, or grandchildren, and could be taken away at any time.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Most Indigenous Australians continued to be denied the right to vote in elections for the Australian Parliament even after 1949.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The *Commonwealth Electoral Act 1962* gave all Aboriginal people the option of enrolling to vote in federal elections.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was not until the *Commonwealth Electoral Amendment Act 1983* that voting became compulsory for Aboriginal people, as it was for other Australians.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Aboriginal people (and all other people) living in the Northern Territory were not allowed to vote in the referendum, which remained the case for both the Northern Territory and the Australian Capital Territory until the Constitutional amendment to section 128 after a referendum in 1977.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is also sometimes mistakenly stated that the 1967 referendum overturned a Flora and Fauna Act.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This is believed to have come from the New South Wales *National Parks and Wildlife Act* 1974, which controlled Aboriginal heritage, land and culture.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The other states had equivalent acts which were managed by various departments, including those relating to agriculture and fishing.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 127 prevented the inclusion of the Indigenous Australians in the official population for constitutional purposes, i.e. their population would not be included in the calculation of the number of seats to assign for each state or in the determination of tax revenue.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The section did not prevent the Bureau of Statistics from counting or collecting other information about Indigenous Australians.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From 1911 to 1966 the Bureau had collected information about Indigenous Australians, however this was published separately to the general population.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Inclusion in the general population was thus important symbolically, but the change did not directly improve the information available to government.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Ninety percent of voters voted yes, and the overwhelming support gave the Federal Government a clear mandate to implement policies to benefit Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Many misconceptions have arisen as to the outcomes of the referendum, some as a result of it taking on a symbolic meaning during a period of increasing Aboriginal self-confidence.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was some five years before any real change occurred as a result of the referendum, but federal legislation has since been enacted covering land rights, discriminatory practices, financial assistance, and preservation of cultural heritage.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was the intention of the government and many voters that this new power was to be only used beneficially.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, in the 1998 case of *Kartinyeri v Commonwealth*, the High Court did not find that such a restriction on the power existed, with the court being split 2:2 (2 judges not deciding) as to whether or not the power could be used to the *detriment* of an identified race.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Hindmarsh Island bridge controversy and the Northern Territory Intervention are two circumstances where the post-1967 race power has arguably been used in this way.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The 1967 referendum has acquired a symbolic meaning in relation to a period of rapid social change during the 1960s.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] As a result, it has been credited with initiating political and social change that was the result of other factors.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The real legislative and political impact of the 1967 referendum has been to enable, and thereby compel, the federal government to take action in the area of Aboriginal Affairs.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Federal governments with a broader national and international agenda have attempted to end the discriminatory practices of state governments such as Queensland and to introduce policies that encourage self-determination and financial security for Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, the effectiveness of these policies has been tempered by an unwillingness of most federal governments to deal with the difficult issues involved in tackling recalcitrant state governments.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It has been argued that Holt, who died not long after the referendum, was setting up a more extensive government response than Gorton enacted.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The benefits of the referendum began to flow to Aboriginal people in 1972.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On 26 January 1972, Aboriginal peoples erected the *Aboriginal Tent Embassy* on the lawns of the Federal Parliament building in Canberra to express their frustration at the lack of progress on land rights and racial discrimination issues.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This became a major confrontation that raised Aboriginal affairs high on the political agenda in the federal election later that year.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] One week after gaining office, the Whitlam government (1972–1975) established a Royal Commission into land rights for Aboriginal people in the Northern Territory under Justice Woodward.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The recommendations were framed in terms to enable application outside the Northern Territory.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The following year, the Fraser government (1975–1983) amended the Aboriginal Land (Northern Territory) Bill by introducing the Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Bill.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This bill was passed as the *Aboriginal Land Rights Act 1976*.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is significant however that this legislation was implemented at all, given the political allegiances of the Fraser government, and shows the level of community support for social justice for Aboriginal people at the time.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Whitlam government used its constitutional powers to overrule racially discriminatory state legislation.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On reserves in Queensland, Aboriginal people were forbidden to gamble, use foul language, undertake traditional cultural practices, indulge in adultery, or drink alcohol.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] They were also required to work without payment.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the Aboriginal Courts in Queensland the same official acted as judge as well as the prosecuting counsel.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Defendants almost invariably pleaded guilty as pleas of not guilty were more than likely to lead to a longer sentence.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Whitlam government, using the race power, enacted the *Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders (Queensland Discriminatory Laws) Act 1975* to override the state laws and eliminate racial discrimination against Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, no federal government ever enforced this Act.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The race power was also used by the Whitlam government to introduce affirmative action in favour of Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It established schemes whereby Aboriginal people could obtain housing, loans, emergency accommodation and tertiary education allowances.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It also increased funding for the Aboriginal Legal Service enabling twenty-five offices to be established throughout Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The race power gained in the 1967 referendum has been used in several other pieces of significant Federal legislation.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] One of the pieces of legislation enacted to protect the Gordon River catchment used the race power but applied it to all people in Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The law prohibited anyone from damaging sites, relics and artefacts of Aboriginal settlement in the Gordon River catchment.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the Tasmanian Dam Case, the High Court held that even though this law applied to all people and not only to Aboriginal people, it still constituted a special law.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the 1992 Mabo judgment, the High Court of Australia established the existence of Native Title in Australian Common Law.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Using the race power, the Keating Government enacted the *Native Title Act 1993* and successfully defended a High Court challenge from the Queensland Government.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In granting the Commonwealth a broad power to legislate in regards to Indigenous Australians, responsibilities for areas traditionally the purview of the states (such as housing, education and healthcare) was shared between both branches of government.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] As a result, both levels have sought to blame the other for the continuing disadvantage of Indigenous Australians, while seeking to place the cost and responsibility to manage these issues on the other.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] When John Howard's Coalition government came to power in 1996, it intervened in the Hindmarsh Island bridge controversy in South Australia with legislation that introduced an exception to the *Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Heritage Protection Act 1984*, to allow the bridge to proceed.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The High Court decided, by a majority, that the amended s.51(xxvi) of the Constitution still allowed the Commonwealth parliament to make laws either for the benefit or to the detriment of a particular race.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] Educated at the University of Otago (1926–29) and the University of Cambridge (1931–33), Trendall was professionally associated with the University of Sydney and Australian National University.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] He was Deputy Vice-Chancellor and Master of University House at the latter institution.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] From 1969 until his death he was Resident Fellow at La Trobe University in Melbourne.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] In January 1940, with the encouragement of the Australian Army, Trendall, together with some colleagues at the University of Sydney, began to study Japanese codes.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] The others were the mathematicians Thomas Gerald Room and Richard Lyons and the classicist Athanasius Treweek.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] In May 1941 Room and Treweek attended a meeting at the Victoria Barracks in Melbourne with the Director of Naval Intelligence of the Royal Australian Navy, several Australian Army intelligence officers and Eric Nave, an expert Japanese cryptographer with the Royal Australian Navy.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] As a result, it was agreed that Room's group, with the agreement of the University of Sydney, would move in August 1941 to work under Nave at the Special Intelligence Bureau in Melbourne.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] In the New Years Honours of 1961, Trendall was appointed a Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George (CMG), in recognition of his service as "Vice-Chancellor" of the Australian National University.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] On 20 July 1961 he was appointed Cavaliere Ufficiale Ordine al Merito della Repubblica Italiana.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] In the Australia Day Honours of 1976, he was appointed a Companion of the Order of Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] In 1997 the Australian Academy of the Humanities, of which Prof.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] Trendall was a Foundation Fellow, inaugurated the Trendall Lectures.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] Some of those were published as printed booklets and others were published online or in the *Humanities Australia* journal.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/a-d-trendall] The Trendall Lecture "alternates between an Australian and an international scholar with a research interest in classical studies" and is delivered in conjunction with the conference of the Australasian Society for Classical Studies.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] The **ACT Heritage Library** is the state library of the Australian Capital Territory (ACT).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] It is the heritage section of the ACT Library and Information Services.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] Antoinette Buchanan has been the Manager of the ACT Heritage Library since 2004.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] The ACT Heritage Library collects, manages and provides access to material relevant to the ACT's documentary heritage.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] It offers assistance in researching matters relating to the ACT, its history and its development.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] The collection of books and journals in the ACT Heritage Library focuses on the works published in the ACT, by ACT residents, or about the ACT.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] Special collections include the collection and a small magazine collection.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] The ACT Heritage Library has a collection of local and regional newspapers in microfilm and print, including newspapers from culturally and linguistically diverse communities and a complete run of Canberra Times from the 1920s.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] The ACT Heritage Library holds 4,000 maps and plans of Canberra and the ACT and plans of some public and private buildings.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] The collection of approximately 200 archives and manuscripts collections in the ACT Heritage Library focuses on local groups and individuals who have made notable contributions to the ACT community.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] Strengths include early childhood education and performing arts.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] The ACT Heritage Library has an extensive ephemera collection of around 300 archive boxes and 2,000 posters, with a particular strength in the performing arts.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] Materials from the collections are being digitised and catalogued in the online database, Images ACT, which currently includes over 8,000 digitised photographs of the ACT and region from the ACT Heritage Library.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] Additional ACT photographs held in national and state institutions, as well those from Images ACT, can be found in the National Library of Australia's digitised collection, Trove.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] The ACT Heritage Library regularly presents small exhibitions and display in their reading room, with additional exhibitions held in the Civic Library building.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] Some items from the ACT Heritage Library were featured in the touring exhibition National Treasures from Australia's Great Libraries, which toured every Australian state capital from 3 December 2005 to late 2007.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] Reflections of Canberra is an online exhibition, sampling the collection of the ACT Heritage Library and reflecting the changing landscape lifestyles of the Canberra region and its community.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] The National Library of Australia and the ACT Heritage Library work cooperatively to ensure the preservation of newspaper titles published in the ACT under the Australian Newspaper Plan.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-heritage-library] The ACT Heritage Library contributes its digitised images from Images ACT to Trove.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-memorial] The **ACT Memorial** is an Australian war memorial honouring men and women associated with the Australian Capital Territory who served in a number of conflicts and peacekeeping missions throughout the world.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-memorial] Located in Canberra, on London Circuit, opposite Civic Square, the ACT Memorial consists of two primary components: a physical memorial, and a web site providing public access to a database of names and information about those honoured by the memorial.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-memorial] The memorial was dedicated on 10 August 2006 by the ACT Chief Minister, Mr Jon Stanhope MLA.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-memorial] The ACT Memorial was designed by local Canberra artist Matthew Harding.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-memorial] It consists of a central illuminated glass sphere which is encompassed by two large stylised wing or feather structures which consist of a number of stainless steel bands.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-memorial] Text on one side of the outer rim at the base of the memorial reads "ACT MEMORIAL" and on the opposite side is the URL for the associated web site.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/act-memorial] On the inner rim under the sphere there are a series of glass tiles with key words related to conflict and sacrifice, such as "peace", "dedication", "resolve", "service", "honour", etc.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The **Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies** (**AIATSIS**), established as the **Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies** (**AIAS**) in 1964, is an independent Australian Government statutory authority.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] It is a collecting, publishing, and research institute and is considered to be Australia's premier resource for information about the cultures and societies of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The institute is a leader in ethical research and the handling of culturally sensitive material.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The collection at AIATSIS has been built through over 50 years of research and engagement with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities and is now a source of language and culture revitalisation, native title research, and Indigenous family and community history.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS is located on Acton Peninsula in Canberra, Australian Capital Territory.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In the late 1950s, there was an increasing focus on the global need for anthropological research into 'disappearing cultures'.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This trend was also emerging in Australia in the work of researchers of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples, leading to a proposal by W.C.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Wentworth MP for the conception of an Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies (AIAS) in 1959.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The proposal was made as a submission to Cabinet, and argued for a more comprehensive approach by the Australian Government to the recording of Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples and cultures.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 1960, a Cabinet sub-committee assessed the proposal and formed a working party at the Australian National University (ANU) to consider the viability of the proposal.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] One of their first actions was to appoint W.E.H.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Stanner to organise a conference on the state of Aboriginal Studies in Australia, to be held in 1961 at the ANU.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Academics and anthropologists in the field of Aboriginal Studies attended the conference, and contributed research papers published in a conference report in 1963.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] No Aboriginal people were present at the conference.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Prime Minister at the time, Robert Menzies, appointed an Interim Council in 1961.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The role of the Interim Council was to plan for a national Aboriginal research organisation and establish how this organisation would interact with existing research and scientific bodies.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Interim Council was also tasked with immediately developing a programme that would identify and address urgent research needs.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Interim Council consisted of 16 members and was chaired by Deputy Vice-Chancellor of the ANU, Professor A.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Trendall, officially recognised as the first chair of the institute now known as AIATSIS.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In August 1962, a draft constitution for the institute was submitted to the Menzies government, and rejected.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Interim Council completed a revised constitution in July 1963.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Amendments to the document included the change from the title 'director' to 'principal' of the institute.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This version of the constitution would go on to form the basis for the creation of the new Australian Institute for Aboriginal Studies the following year.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies was established as a statutory authority under an Act of Parliament in June 1964.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The mission of the Institute at that time has been described as "to record language, song, art, material culture, ceremonial life and social structure before those traditions perished in the face of European ways".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This notion is also reflected in the Institute's official functions, as recorded in the Reading of the Bill in Parliament.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] 2. to treat as a matter of urgency those studies for which the source materials are disappearing.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] 3. to establish and conduct a documentation centre on the Aborigines, and a library of books, manuscripts and other relevant material, both for the use of scholars and for public education.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] 4. to encourage co-operation with and between scholars in universities, museums, and other institutions engaged in studies of the Aborigines, and with appropriate private bodies.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] 5. to publish and to support the publication of the results of research.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] 6. to co-operate with appropriate bodies concerning the financing of research, the preservation of sites, and the collection of records.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] 7. to promote as and when necessary the training of research workers.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] 8. to establish and maintain relations with relevant international bodies.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIAS had a twenty-two member Council, composed mainly of academics, and had a foundation membership of one hundred.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The founding Principal of the newly formed institute was Frederick McCarthy, a professional anthropologist and graduate of Sydney University who had spent nearly 30 years working in the field.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The creation of the AIAS provided an opportunity for greater cross-discipline interaction in fields relating to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander studies in Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Institute's founding principal, Fred McCarthy, was an advocate of film as an important part of research methodology as early as his tenure as curator of anthropology at the Australian Museum in Sydney in the 1940s.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This was evident in the contributions he made during his involvement in establishing the AIAS and also as its principal, in continuing to support the development of the AIAS Film Unit and championing ethnographic film in global forums.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In the early years of the AIAS, the Film Unit largely outsourced early filmmaking work to other companies, or worked in collaboration with the Commonwealth Film Unit (as early as 1962).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] But over the next 30 years, the Film Unit would go on to produce "one of the largest assembly of ethnographic films created in the world".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In keeping with the AIAS official function "to publish and to support the publication of the results of research", a publishing arm of the institute was established in 1964.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Publishing under the name Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies, the publishing arm released a range of papers and research findings, including in the fields of linguistics, demography, physical anthropology, history and musicology.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The early work of the AIAS is credited with increasing interaction between academics in different fields, as well as establishing the foundations for the extensive collections AIATSIS holds today.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] But before 1970, there had never been an Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander member on the AIAS Council.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The 1970s marked a period of change for the AIAS.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This began with the appointment of the first Aboriginal member of the AIAS Council in 1970.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Phillip Roberts, an Alawa man, served on the council from September 1970 until June 1972.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This was followed in 1971 with a second Aboriginal Council member, Senator Neville Bonner, who served on Council until 1974 and for a second term in the late 1970s.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] And again in 1972, with the appointment of Dick Roughsey to replace Phillip Roberts at the end of his term.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The appointment of Phillip Roberts to the Council reflected a growing pressure for an increase in Aboriginal representation within the institute.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] But the move did not allay the belief held by some Aboriginal activists that the AIAS was engaging in 'tokenism' in the extent to which Aboriginal people were involved in the administration of Aboriginal Studies.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The changes to the Institute that would take place in the following decade were also influenced by the shifting social and political landscape in Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Aboriginal rights movement was growing and Aboriginal people were demanding a voice on Council, consultation with communities and an increased focus on projects relevant to the needs of Indigenous people.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 1972, the Whitlam government was elected.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Their policy of self-determination for Aboriginal people echoed calls for greater Aboriginal involvement in the administration and functions of the AIAS.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The new government was also responsible for a significant boost to AIAS funding.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The appointment of Peter Ucko in 1972 as Principal of the AIAS has since been described as the beginning of an increase in involvement of Aboriginal people in the workings of the institute.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In his time as Principal, Ucko was responsible for implementing a policy later labelled "Aboriginalisation", which was aimed at opening up the institute to Aboriginal involvement and representation.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This policy was influenced by a document circulated in 1974, called the Eaglehawk and Crow letter, which criticised the current model of academic research.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The policy and structural changes to the Institute continued throughout the 1970s.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Aboriginal Advisory Committee was established in 1975, and consisted of the six Aboriginal members of the AIAS Council.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Early recommendations including increased representation of Aboriginal people on committees and the AIAS Council as well as employment at the institute.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The committee was renamed in 1978, to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Advisory Committee.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 1975–1976, a category of research grants for Aboriginal researchers was introduced.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The emergence of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people filling the role of 'cultural practitioner', travelling to the AIAS to provide advice on projects and research being undertaken, was also documented from around 1976 onwards.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The time Peter Ucko spent as Principal of the AIAS saw a phase of "rapid expansion" for the institute.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The AIAS Film Unit that had operated in Sydney until 1973 was re-established in Canberra in 1975.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Prominent American-born ethnographic filmmaker David MacDougall was appointed the Director of this new AIAS Film Unit.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] With his wife and filmmaking partner Judith MacDougall and Kim McKenzie, the Film Unit operated until 1988 when its functions were absorbed back into the institute.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] During the MacDougall/McKenzie era, a new style of ethnographic film was explored.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] One that moved away from film as a scientific record in favour of telling the story of individuals lives.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The filmmakers also practised a more collaborative approach to their films, and chose to use translations and subtitles to give direct access to the subjects voice and thoughts rather than the dominant 'voice of god' narration style.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] One of the most notable films produced towards the end of this period was *Waiting for Harry*, a prize-winning film directed by Kim McKenzie with anthropologist Les Hiatt and now considered to exemplify the "style of collaborative filmmaking" the Film Unit favoured in their work.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The power of film to "influence opinion" was becoming increasingly recognised and with this, the lack of representation of Aboriginal people telling their own stories.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 1978, a meeting chaired by prominent activist and academic Marcia Langton expressed these concerns, arguing for greater access to film and video in Aboriginal communities, and training in film production by the AIAS.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] By the following year, the AIAS Film Unit had begun to implement a training program and had started employing trainee Aboriginal filmmakers on productions by the early 1980s.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The AIAS began presenting a biennial Wentworth Lecture in 1978, named as a tribute to W.C.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Wentworth for his role in establishing the institute.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The lecture is presented by prominent person with knowledge or experience relating to issues affecting Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples in Australia today.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The expansion of the Institute continued into the 1980s.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Aboriginal Studies Press began publishing the Australian Aboriginal Studies Journal in 1983, a peer-reviewed journal aimed at "promoting high-quality research in Australian Indigenous studies".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 1982, the AIAS established a task force that identified the prevailing need for further 'Aboriginalisation' of the Institute's workforce.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] At the time, there were four Aboriginal staff members, making up around 7% of the total staff.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This was followed in 1985 with the creation of the role of Aboriginal Studies Coordination Officer within the AIAS, whose responsibilities involved improving access for Aboriginal people to the research and resources of the institute.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The *After 200 Years* project was launched in 1985, aiming to fill some of the gaps in the AIAS photographic collection; particularly images of daily life in the southern, urban parts of Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Aboriginal involvement in selecting subject matter, photographing and documenting the collection was a major part of the project.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The three-year project culminated in the publication of a book containing hundreds of photographs of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, and selected by them to represent their community.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Rock Art Protection Program (RAPP) commenced in 1986 following a request for such an initiative by the then Minister of Aboriginal Affairs Clyde Holding.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The aim of the RAPP was to protect Australian Indigenous rock art.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Grants were approved by the institute to fund various projects related to rock art protection.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The collections were also expanding, and by 1987 the AIATSIS library encompassed the print collections, a special Bibliographic Section and the Resource Centre (which contained the Institute's audiovisual materials).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Between 1987 and 1989, the survival of the AIAS as an independent statutory body was tied to a proposal for a new statutory commission that would take over all aspects of the Aboriginal Affairs portfolio.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This commission would become the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC), conceived in an Act of Parliament in 1989.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The AIAS would not be folded into this commission; instead it would be recreated under a new Act with a new name.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The *Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies (AIATSIS) Act* was passed by parliament in 1989, replacing the AIAS Act.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The newly established AIATSIS had a reduced Council consisting of nine members, with the AIATSIS Act specifying that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people hold a minimum of five of these Council positions.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The new Act also established a Research Advisory Committee, to assess research applications and advise the council.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Aboriginal Studies Press published their best-selling Aboriginal Australia map in 1996, based on research conducted for the Encyclopaedia of Aboriginal Australia, edited by David Horton.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 2001, the Institute launched a two-year Library Digitisation Pilot Program (LDPP).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Among the items digitised, catalogued and made available online were 267 volumes of the *Dawn* and *New Dawn* magazines held in the AIATSIS collection.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS also distributed over 2000 free copies of these magazines on CD-Rom, to Indigenous organisations, schools and libraries in New South Wales.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Throughout this period, AIATSIS continued to undertake projects focused on the digitisation of collection materials, including their holdings of the complete back catalogue of *Koori Mail*.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This involved scanning over 35,000 pages from 500 editions of the newspaper, with searchable copies launched on the AIATSIS website in partnership with Koori Mail in 2011.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] As part of their research functions, AIATSIS also initiated a number of public programs and research related events during this time that are still run today.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The institute has convened the National Indigenous Studies Conference every two years since 2001 and the National Native Title Conference every year since 2002.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The *After 200 Years* photographic project was revisited in 2014 with an exhibition of images at Parliament House, Canberra, to coincide with AIATSIS' 50-year anniversary.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 2020, following consultation with the United Ngunnawal Elders Council and the Winanggaay Ngunnawal Language Group, the AIATSIS building in Acton was officially named *Maraga*, which means a strong shield.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] On 2 February 2024, coinciding with its 60th anniversary, AIATSIS opened a new facility in Mparntwe-Alice Springs, building on its long partnership with First Nations Media Australia, which is based in the city.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS staff, six of whom are Indigenous locals (of seven in total; intended to grow to up to 24) located at the new centre will work closely with local people to take care of the cultural heritage from the region.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] There is a dedicated ancestry section in the new centre, which before its completion was referred to as AIATSIS Alice Springs Engagement and Digitisation Centre and is now officially known as AIATSIS Central Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The centre will be run in collaboration with the Northern Territory Government, and allow access to AIATSIS materials for people living in Central Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] An exhibition titled *To Know, To Respect, To Care* is on at the centre until 14 June 2024.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The official opening was attended by Linda Burney, the Minister for Indigenous Australians, and NT Minister for Arts, Culture and Heritage Chansey Paech.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS is an Australian Government statutory authority established under the *Public Governance, Performance and Accountability Act 2013*.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] As of 2024 it is under the portfolio of the Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet, and Hon Linda Burney, Minister for Indigenous Australians, is the responsible minister.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] 6. to encourage understanding, in the general community, of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander societies.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The AIATSIS Council is a governing body designed to oversee and steer the functions and direction of the institute.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The role and responsibilities of the council are mandated in the *AIATSIS Act 1989*.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Council consists of nine members; four are elected by the institute's membership and five appointed by the Minister.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] According to the AIATSIS Act 1989, one person appointed by the Minister must be a Torres Strait Islander and the four other people appointed by the Minister must be Aboriginal persons or Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The four Council members elected by the Institute's membership must be members themselves.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Various advisory committees exist to assist the Council as well as the chief executive officer (CEO).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Indigenous Caucus is a working group providing a forum for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander staff to meet and discuss workplace issues.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Indigenous Caucus was revitalised in 2003–2004 and contributed to the development of policies and procedures in that year, notably AIATSIS' Indigenous Training and Career Development Plan.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 2013, the Indigenous Caucus developed a formal Service Charter and elected an Executive consisting of three members.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Native Title Research Advisory Committee (NTRAC) provides advice to the CEO on the research program of the Native Title Research Unit.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Research Advisory Committee (RAC) is responsible for assessing and advising on AIATSIS research projects and programs, including research grants.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] RAC functions are established in the AIATSIS Act.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Research Ethics Committee (REC) is responsible for advising AIATSIS on the ethics of the research proposals by staff or grantees of AIATSIS, as well as research carried out through the Institute's external collaborations.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The roles in the Research Ethics Committee are based on the National Statement published by the National Health and Medical Research Council.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The AIATSIS Act sets the organisation the task of conducting, facilitating and promoting research in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies and training Indigenous researchers.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] For over 50 years, AIATSIS has conducted research across a range of areas of study relevant to Indigenous peoples, culture, heritage, knowledge and experiences.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This has led to a diverse research history; from languages and archaeological research, land rights, and political engagement, to contemporary topics in health and commerce.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The AIATSIS collections not only contain priceless records of Australia's Indigenous cultural heritage, but provide a significant national and international research infrastructure for research by, for and about Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS is one of Australia's Publicly Funded Research Agencies (PFRA), alongside organisations such as CSIRO and the Australian Institute of Marine Science.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS is Australia's only non-science PFRA.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Currently AIATSIS undertakes research in six priority areas.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The institute is a leader in ethical research and the handling of culturally sensitive material. and holds in its collections many unique and irreplaceable items of cultural, historical and spiritual significance.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS published the *Guidelines for Ethical Research in Australian Indigenous Studies* (referred to as GERAIS) in 1999.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This was a document considered to be the leading ethics guidelines for conducting research in and with Indigenous communities in Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] GERAIS was regularly revised and significantly updated in 2012.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] GERAIS was replaced in 2020 by *AIATSIS Code of Ethics for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Research (the AIATSIS Code)*, which supersedes GERAIS.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Accompanying it is "A Guide to applying The AIATSIS Code of Ethics for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Research".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 2013, AIATSIS was involved in the review of two National Health and Medical Research Council research ethics guidelines relating to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander health research.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS began undertaking native title research activities through the Native Title Research Unit in 1993, following the 1992 *Mabo v Queensland* High Court decision.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Native Title Research Advisory Committee, the Research Advisory Committee, and the AIATSIS Council oversee the work conducted in Native Title and traditional ownership research at AIATSIS.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS conducts a range of research projects relating to Native Title and traditional ownership, including Native Title and cultural heritage, Native Title and fresh and sea water, and Prescribed Body Corporates.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The role of Native Title research at AIATSIS is to monitor outcomes of Native Title and through research and study, provide advice on Native Title policy development.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Institute publishes a range of materials relating to Native Title including books, discussion papers, research reports and a Native Title Newsletter.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS also provides a Native Title Research and Access Officer, who is responsible for assisting Native Title claimants to access materials from the AIATSIS collections in support of their claim.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Up until 2019, AIATSIS also contributed to Native Title policy and research by co-organising the Annual National Native Title Conference.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] However, in 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic in Australia, the conference was cancelled, and in 2021 it merged with the National Indigenous Research Conference, creating a five-day event known as the AIATSIS Summit.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS publishes a number of resources for anyone wishing to undertake research into their own family history.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The *Family History kit* is aimed at providing the basics for tracing Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander heritage.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] It contains guides to AIATSIS' own resources, including the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Biographical Index (ABI) and digitised collection materials, as well as guides to external resources that may help with family history research.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] General guidance is also provided regarding research resources specific to Indigenous family history research, historical name conventions and usage and confirmation of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander heritage.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS also provides research support to Link-Up case workers and researchers around Australia, who are assisting members of the Stolen Generations to reconnect with their family and heritage.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In keeping with its mandated functions, AIATSIS publishes the results of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies through their publishing arm, Aboriginal Studies Press (ASP).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Institute began publishing in 1962 with *A demographic survey of the Aboriginal population of the Northern Territory, with special reference to Bathurst Island Mission*.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This and other early publications were released under the imprint Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies, the former title of AIATSIS.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The ASP publishing imprint was trademarked in 2002, but was operating as the publishing arm of AIATSIS as early as the publication of Helen Ross' *Just For Living* in 1987.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The **AIATSIS Research Publications** became an imprint in 2011 and its stated purpose is to publish scholarly research that is derived from the AIATSIS Research Program.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] All Aboriginal Studies Press-branded titles are peer-reviewed and the majority are published concurrently in print and several ebook formats.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The first phone app was published in 2013, and was shortlisted for the 2013 Mobile Awards.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Titles published by ASP have included research reports, monographs, biographies, autobiographies, family and community histories, and children's books.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Since 2005 the list has aligned more closely with the Institute's research focus.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Most publications derive from academic research, some funded by AIATSIS.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] ASP publishes books by both Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander and non-Indigenous authors who are writing in the field of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In some cases Aboriginal authors, like Doreen Kartinyeri and Joan Martin, have chosen to write in collaboration with non-Aboriginal oral historians.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Publishing Advisory Committee makes recommendations to the AIATSIS Principal and Aboriginal Studies Press about which manuscripts to publish from those submitted.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] It has relationships with distributors and resellers for both national and international print and ebook distribution.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Another widely used resource published by Aboriginal Studies Press is the **Aboriginal Australia map**, created by David Horton.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Aboriginal Australia map represents the general locations of larger groupings of Aboriginal people, using research that was conducted during the development of *The Encyclopaedia of Aboriginal Australia*, which was another significant ASP publication.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Previous milestone publications included the book *After 200 Years*, a collaboration showcasing photographs and stories of Aboriginal people as selected by members of those communities.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Both books are now out of print and only available in libraries.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] ASP also publishes the Stanner Award winner for a scholarly manuscript (not fiction or poetry) by an Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander, which recognises the importance of being published to emerging academics.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The prize includes mentoring and editorial support by ASP, as well as publication of the manuscript, A$5,000, and a glass sculpture by Jenni Kemarre Martiniello.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The biennial award is named in honour of the anthropologist W.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] (Bill) Stanner, who played an important role in establishing the AIAS, and the ongoing development of the institute.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 1996, *Auntie Rita*, a biography of Rita Huggins co-written by her and her daughter Jackie Huggins, won the award.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Anna Haebich won the 1999 award for her work *Broken circles: Fragmenting indigenous families 1800–2000*.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The 2011 award was won by human rights advocate and lawyer Hannah McGlade in 2011.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The AIATSIS website hosts the **AUSTLANG** database, an informative source of information on all known Aboriginal Australian languages.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] With its beginnings on a card file compiled in the 1990s, the Indigenous Languages Database (ILDB) was developed based on the Language Thesaurus maintained by the AIATSIS library since the 1960s.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The online version of AUSTLANG was developed in 2005, revised and released to the public in 2008, and after more redevelopment work, a refined version was released in 2018.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS hosts a range of special events and research workshops, symposiums and conferences.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS is located on the Acton Peninsula in a building that was newly built for the Institute and opened in 2001.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The building was officially opened by the Honourable W.C.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] As part of the opening the Ngunnawal people, the traditional owners of the land on which the AIATSIS building stands performed a Welcome to Country and smoking ceremony, and the Anbarra people from North Central Arnhem Land performed a friendship ceremony, known as the Rom ceremony.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The architect, Howard Ragatt of the firm Ashton Raggatt McDougall designed the building for AIATSIS and for its neighbour on the Acton Peninsula, the National Museum of Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] During design of the AIATSIS building, it was reoriented from original plans to save two apple box trees that were identified as significant to the Peninsula.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The building cost $13.75 million and was funded by the Commonwealth Government's Centenary of Federation Grants Program.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The design of the AIATSIS building has been the subject of differing interpretations.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The rear of the building has been described as a black copy of pioneer architect Le Corbusier's 1920s Villa Savoye in France.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The architect, Howard Raggatt, was quoted as confirming this influence but has also stated that it is designed to be reminiscent of Sidney Nolan's famous paintings of Ned Kelly.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] A new building is planned in Canberra, to be located in a precinct to be named Ngurra, on the shores of Lake Burley Griffin, in the Parliamentary Triangle.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The new precinct A$316.5 million will also include a new centre for learning and knowledge, and a resting place for ancestral remains of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people from around the nation who are unable to be located in their Country.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The name *Ngurra* occurs in several Aboriginal languages, meaning "home", "camp", "a place of belonging or inclusion".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] A design competition was held in 2022 to select the architects for the project.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] A new AIATSIS facility known as AIATSIS Central Australia was opened on 2 February 2024 in Alice Springs/Mparntwe, to serve Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people in Central Australia.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The offices and exhibition spaces were created from two vacant retail premises in Todd Mall.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] AIATSIS is considered to be Australia's premier resource for information about the cultures and societies of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] AIATSIS is the only Commonwealth of Australia institution responsible for collecting and maintaining materials documenting the oral and visual traditions and histories of Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The Institute identifies its collection as a "keeping place for culturally significant objects" that is "a resource for anybody looking to improve their knowledge of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander history and culture".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The institute's holdings represent thousands of years of history and more than 500 Australian Indigenous languages, dialects and groups.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] This collection supports, and is a result of, research in the fields of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] An independent assessment in 2014 confirmed that AIATSIS holds over 6 million feet of film, over 40,000 hours of audio, 12,800 unpublished manuscripts and record series, 653,000 photographs, and 120,000 print and published materials (3,000 of which are rare books) among other miscellanea.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] As of 2024 it was estimated that it holds over a million cultural items, which include 42,000 hours of audio, over 700,000 photographs, and around 6 million feet of film.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The Audiovisual Archives also holds copies of the first audio recorded in Australia; a series of ethnographic wax cylinder recordings made in the Torres Strait Islands in 1898.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The Cambridge Anthropological Expedition to the Torres Strait, led by Alfred Cort Haddon, recorded songs and speech from Mer/Murray Island, Mabuiag/Jervis Island, Saibai Island, Tudu Island and Iama/Yam Island.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Since the establishment of the Institute in 1964, the AIATSIS collection has been developed through acquisition by donation, gift and purchase or, through materials created and collected during the work of ethnographic field researchers and filmmakers funded by the AIATSIS grants program.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The collection has also been built through deposits of materials, an arrangement which permits the original owners to assign access and use conditions appropriate to the cultural information contained in the items.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Once material has been acquired by AIATSIS, the Institute faces the challenges of maintaining a cultural resource collection.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] This is achieved through a collection management plan that involves processes of recording and cataloguing, and appropriate storage and handling to extend the life of physical items and preserving their content through format shifting.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Storage of collection items in climate-controlled vaults, to maintain their integrity and to minimise contact with deteriorating agents such as moisture and light.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The Institute also follows international archiving guidelines for the storage and preservation of materials.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] There are a wide variety of analogue photograph, tape and film formats held in the AIATSIS collection, which pose special preservation and future access risks.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The age of some of these formats and materials, combined with the varying conditions in which they were stored prior to their acquisition by AIATSIS, heightens the deterioration of the media.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Another preservation issue inherent in these analogue materials is the machines that can play back that particular format, as in some cases the material and the playback device are no longer manufactured.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] To manage these risks and maintain future access to the collection, preservation of the actual content contained in collection items is also achieved through a program of digitisation.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Due to the potential issues of long-term archiving and storage of digital items, the opposite process is often employed to ensure access and preservation.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] In the case of digital publications and manuscripts, the originals will often be printed and incorporated into the print collections as an additional preservation measure.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The AIATSIS collection holds material that is sensitive and/or secret/sacred to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] In accordance with its founding Act, and as part of their collection management plan, AIATSIS adheres to strict protocols when handling and processing these sensitive items.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The institute also supports and adheres to the protocols developed by the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Library, Information and Resource Network (ATSILIRN).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Restricted visual media such as photographs and printed items are stored separately to the rest of the collection and audio and moving image items are not played until any cultural requirements are checked.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Restricted material must also be carefully handled during digitisation, which means that the work is carried out in secured conditions such as enclosed booths and by staff that can meet the protocols of the item being digitised.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] AIATSIS launched its Library Digitisation Pilot Program in 2001, before which the Library had no dedicated digitisation equipment or policies for managing digital materials.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] This two-year program was originally funded by the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC), and involved the creation of digital collections across the institution.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Since then AIATSIS has continued to incorporate digitisation of the collection into its management plan, but have publicly stated that an increase in funding is required for the institute to digitise some of the at risk formats held in the collection before those items are lost.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Given these limitations, AIATSIS prioritises the selection of materials for digitisation using factors including significance of the item/s, the level of deterioration, cultural protocols, copyright status, and client demand.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] One of the identified priorities of the program is to digitise and preserve all of the audiovisual collection currently on endangered magnetic tape formats by the 2025 deadline set by UNESCO.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The collection is housed in the AIATSIS building on Acton Peninsula and is accessible through a number of resources.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The AIATSIS Library is open to the public and holds a range of printed materials including manuscripts, journals, readers in different Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander languages, dictionaries, published books and rare books, maps, and posters.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Access to AIATSIS' print and manuscript collections can be made through the Library's Stanner Reading Room and the film, sound and pictorial collections by appointment through the Access Unit.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] These physical access points are open limited hours.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The AIATSIS Digitisation Program contributes to increased access to the collection; whether access is through on site resources, the provision of copies of materials or the sharing of the collection online.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Due to increasing obsolescence of analogue formats, AIATSIS identifies digitisation as the way to preserve those items for future generations to access.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] This is considered to be particularly important for facilitating "remote access by Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities" as well as for access by researchers and the general public.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The AIATSIS Access Unit runs a program called Return of Material to Indigenous Communities (ROMTIC), through which Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander clients are provided with up to twenty copies of collection materials that relate to their language group or family.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] This service is limited to items that have been preserved, so AIATSIS' digitisation program has allowed an increasing number of digital items available to ROMTIC clients.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] AIATSIS also makes the collection available through a series of online exhibitions and digitised collection material published on their website.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Access to the AIATSIS collection is also dictated by legislation governing the Institute and in some instances by legal agreements outlining the terms under which collection materials can be used.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The terms for access to the AIATSIS collection are in the first instance set by the AIATSIS Act, Section 41.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The conditions referred to in Section 41(1) of the AIATSIS Act are usually covered in the agreement that AIATSIS enters into when material is deposited.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] These agreements, along with the section 41(2) of the Act, can govern the way that unpublished material can be accessed and used.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Access to and use of material in the AIATSIS collection is also subject to the terms set out in the Copyright Act (1968).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] When a donation or deposit is being made, AIATSIS requests to be made aware of any sensitive items included in the material.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The secret or sacred nature of information contained in many collection items is an important factor in access to the AIATSIS collection.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] In response to these complex issues AIATSIS developed an overarching Access and Use Policy in 2014, to "manage legal and cultural rights over material while maximising accessibility".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] Since its inception, AIATSIS has developed and maintained a range of resources to enhance discoverability of the collection.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] One of the most significant of these resources is the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Biographical Index (ABI).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The ABI had its beginnings in 1979 as a non-selective biographical register of names, constructed using information on Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people from published material in the collection.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] In the early years of the biographical register, it was hoped it could "provide an important record of the achievements of Aboriginal people, and be a source of pride for generations to come".
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] The former Perfect Pictures Database appears to have been superseded by the Photographic Collection, which contains around 400,000 (and growing) digitised images, and more than 700,000 images in total.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] For copyright and cultural reasons, the images may only be viewed in the Stanner Reading Room, but caption information is available online, and copies of the images may be requested.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p02] AIATSIS also hosts or contributes to other online resources, aimed at facilitating access to and understanding of the collection.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
